sec.p:
The family Bathycrinidae comprises ten-armed stalked crinoids that are widely distributed in the deep sea. Three species in this family have been recorded from the Western Atlantic: Bathycrinus aldrichianus Thomson, 1872 , B. australis A.H. Clark, 1907 a
and Monachocrinus caribbeus (
A.H. Clark, 1908 )
(
A.M. Clark, 1977 ; Gislén, 1938, 1951;
Macurda & Meyer, 1976 ;
Meyer et al. , 1978 ;
Roux et al. , 2002 ;
Eléaume et al. , 2012 ). A new species was collected off the Bahamas at a depth of 4,243–4,558 meters. It is assigned to the recently established genus Discolocrinus Mironov, 2008 which formerly comprised a single species D. thieli Mironov, 2008 from the deep Eastern Pacific.

The systematic position of the genus Naumachocrinus A.H. Clark, 1912 remains questionable. It has been referred either to Bathycrinidae (
Bourseau et al. , 1991 ;
Hess, 2011 ;
Oji & Kitazawa, 2008 ;
Roux et al. , 2002 ) or Caledonicrinidae ( Mironov, 2000 , 2008 ).
Mironov ( 2000 )
suggested that Naumachocrinus be referred to subfamily Caledonicrininae , because both Caledonicrinus and Naumachocrinus display a terminal attachment disk and extremely developed radials. The basal circlet is very reduced in Naumachocrinus and cryptic in Caledonicrinus . In addition, the middle and distal columnals are articulated by synarthries without deep ligament fossae, and the fulcral ridge in the distal columnals has irregular relief (
Bourseau et al. , 1991 ;
Roux et al. , 2002 ). But these features may be convergent with Caledonicrinus (see also
Hess, 2011 , p. 155 ). Further, information on the pinnule structure and knobby processes is presently lacking for Naumachocrinus .
